We measure our worth based on the size of our contributions to society. A life meaningful is one that has changed the course of humankind; a life meaningful is one that makes us remembered. We look up to the greats and aspire to be them â in essence, we live to change the lives of others on a grand scale.
When we go by this scale, this measure of worth, the vast majority of us are simply not meaningful; certainly, what we have done is less impressive than the work of Plato or Socrates, than the work of Newton or Einstein or whatever famous name immediately comes to mind. The greats are great because they are few and far between. Our self-worth suffers as a result, for we see that we are simply not up to par, that what we have done is orders of magnitude less impressive.
Why must we live in such a self-deprecating manner?
Indeed, most of us will not single-handedly change the course of humankind, but comparing ourselves with those who do is pointless â we must note that the very act of comparing is relative. We could compare ourselves to the greats, but we could always go greater still to view our impact on the planets, on the universe. None of us, whether we be the next masters or not, could change the course of our planet, much less the universe in all of its grand infinitude. The earth will continue to follow its steady path around the Sun (and I dearly hope that I will not change that) and time will continue to march on as has time immemorial. Given that I cannot change the course of the Earth, am I too worthless?
Obviously not.
Itâs easy to feel worthless when compared with others, but comparison is futile; there will always be someone more capable, someone more wealthy, someone more intelligent, someone who makes a greater contribution. And thatâs okay. We do not start off on equal footing; we will not end on equal footing. We all have our own niches, our roles to fulfill. 
A meaningful life is one in which we do our best with the roles that we have, roles that we are passionate about. Our lives may not be impressive enough to have our names inscribed in the annals of history, but they donât have to be. You could not replace me and expect the exact same results -- that is enough for me.
            I live to contribute, no matter how small the contribution, how small the resulting change. While I may not change much by myself, the combined efforts of everyone will have some larger impact; we naturally build off the work of another. Society does not advance on the shoulders of a few, but on the backs of us all. If everyone makes some slight contribution, then we will all have had lives worth living.
